I think there's going to be an ongoing demand for meaning that vaccines
aren't going to ameliorate. I'll see about some text notes prior to our
next call, thanks!

Huge congratulations on Best Men's Stage Monologues; very nicely done and
well earned! Agreed that it's very exciting to hear their selection also -
will be curious to read it!

All best wishes,
Josh


On Thu, Jan 14, 2021 at 7:33 PM Richard Manley <antiqueroman@yahoo.com>
wrote:
>
> I thought that the latest version of pdf allowed for marginalia, but I
haven't tried.  Regardless, here it is in Word.  Thanks for taking the time
to comment.  There is going to be a collective sigh all over the world when
the pandemic dies - the zeitgeist.  I wonder if there is a possible overlap
of some kind, between my journal entries and a need to make sense of it
all.   No ideas, just wondering.
>
> On a separate, but not entirely unrelated note, I found out yesterday
that Smith & Kraus (one of the three principal theater publishers) is going
to include a monologue from my newest full-length teenage play in their
2021 anthology, Best Men's Stage Monologues.  It's based on a national
judging of all the plays produced and submitted last year in the US.  These
collections are used primarily by actors when planning an audition, and
sometimes by directors to train actors.  Other monologues of mine have been
published before, but the most rewarding aspect of this choice is that they
picked a monologue spoken by a 16 yr.old boy.  Unusual for a publication
that caters to the theater world, where very few plays (outside of NY) that
are written for and about young people are taken seriously.
>
